Now for the fix: The bug is the extra `r.advance()` after consuming the letter sequence. Remove that line.

Also note: The method is `void read(Tokeniser t, CharacterReader r)`. In the first if block, after consuming the letter sequence, we should not advance. So we remove `r.advance();`. Also, we should ensure that `r.consumeLetterSequence()` already consumed the letters, so the reader is at the next character after the letters. So no need to advance.

Thus the fixed code:

```
        void read(Tokeniser t, CharacterReader r) {
            if (r.matchesLetter()) {
                String name = r.consumeLetterSequence();
                t.tagPending.appendTagName(name.toLowerCase());
                t.dataBuffer.append(name);
                // r.advance(); // BUG: removed
                return;
            }

            if (t.isAppropriateEndTagToken() && !r.isEmpty()) {
                char c = r.consume();
                switch (c) {
                    case '\t':
                    case '\n':
                    case '\f':
                    case ' ':
                        t.transition(BeforeAttributeName);
                        break;
                    case '/':
                        t.transition(SelfClosingStartTag);
                        break;
                    case '>':
                        t.emitTagPending();
                        t.transition(Data);
                        break;
                    default:
                        t.dataBuffer.append(c);
                        anythingElse(t, r);
                        break;
                }
            } else {
                anythingElse(t, r);
            }
        }
```

